w guilds that don't follow it. They usually come right out and say that, and really, there's not a lot anyone can do about it. Then, you have the guilds that will abuse the calendar. Say you have a limit of how many total raids you can have scheduled. They do things like have members post &quot;open&quot; raids in order to get more, or 2 or more smaller guilds that raid together will each take their alloted raids, doubling, tripling, or even more their raids over others. Finally, most of the few that are still following the calendar in word and spirit, will get fed up with it, and the server goes total FFA. <br><br>Calendars are and FCFS system. First guild to post on a out-of-game calendar gets the mob. How is that really different than the first guild with the force to take the mob there in the zone getting it? <br><br>When all it's said and done, everything hinges on guilds being civil to each other. If a guild is there and prepping for a mob, and another guild shows up, the second guild should back off, and not pressure them to go before they are ready. They can then expect the same respectful treatment for themselves.  <p><h6><a href="mailto:cuchulaine_eq@hotmail.com">Geneze Angelfyre</a><br>Templar of Tunare<br>Veterans Legion<br>Luclin<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=32057">my crap</a></h6></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub96.ezboard.com/ucerosofvazaelle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ceros of Vazaelle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Level 13, Advanced Beggar</span><br>  Posts: 48<br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/17/02 9:17:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub96.ezboard.com/fkanebaylecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=196.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: To FFA or not to FFA?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> You seem to be an arrogant bunch on Xegony. If the rest of the server whants a calendar system, you'll have to abide by it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Uh, no.  SOE does not recognize calendars and will not enforce them.  So if only one guild on the server is FFA, there's nothing you can do aside from getting there first.  <br><br>Calendars are completely voluntary and are only useful as a communication tool.  They are a throwback to an older age of EQ. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub96.ezboard.com/usiranui.showPublicProfile?language=EN>siranui</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Level 2, Generic Newbie</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/17/02 9:39:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub96.ezboard.com/fkanebaylecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=196.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: To FFA or not to FFA?</span><hr size=1> <br>Torvo uses a reservation system and barring a few incedents, it's worked for two years. <br><br>Torvo also has the nicest community feeling of any server that I've played on. It's friendly and helpful and because there's not so much 'FCFS' competition, guilds are more willing to help each other do things...making everyone enjoy the game (and it IS a game) more. <br><br>  Hell of a lot more people get their epics this way for a start.... and we do all want our epics, right? Imagine wanting to finish your epic and your guild 'don't DO 'x' plane' any more or lack the capacity. Now imagine instead being able to turn to 30 non-guildies who aren't going to say 'Like hell are we getting you a rezz stick... then your guild might compete AoW (or whatever) spawns with us.'<br><br>I'm wondering how many people will still be screaming FFA if theirs isn't the top-dog guild; as let's face it... 95% of us aren't going to be... think now about what it's going to feel like if you are one of that 95% that is shut out of the End Game.<br><br>If you want to dictate a 'hostile' server before you know you're going to be able to dictate terms, you're getting a little shortsighted.<br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub96.ezboard.com/ucerosofvazaelle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ceros of Vazaelle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Level 13, Advanced Beggar</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/17/02 10:19:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub96.ezboard.com/fkanebaylecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=196.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: To FFA or not to FFA?</span><hr size=1> Different people play EQ for different reasons.  You play the game to be friendly and helpful to everyone?  You want to share spawns evenly and help the most casual player get primal?  Excellent.<br><br>Just don't expect others to conform to your view.  Some people enjoy the competitive nature of EQ, and I can tell you that there are a lot of those here.<br><br>Some people find questing to be fun, others like to exp, and there are those who like to roleplay.  There are also players who play competitively and enjoy racing to spawns, who play to be the best, and are very dedicated. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub96.ezboard.com/ucuchulainekynthelig.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cuchulaine Kynthelig</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Level 13, Advanced Beggar</span><br>  Posts: 19<br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/17/02 10:51:45 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub96.ezboard.com/fkanebaylecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=196.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: To FFA or not to FFA?</span><hr size=1> FCFS doesn't have to be hostile. A calendar (just another form of FCFS) isn't necessarily without hostility. I've seen some pretty nasty things come about because of calendar abuse. I've also seen some pretty nice races for important mobs, where the losing guild backed off and cheered the other guild on. I've seen them where, when the first guild failed, the next one would CR them. <br><br>As a matter of fact, people are tons more friendly and easy-going in the game than they are on any message board. Flame-fests on message boards are always far, far worse than the incidents that precipitated them. Therefore, doesn't it seem better to handle things like this IN-GAME?<br><br>You can make all the arguments you want, but some guild simply won't follow a calendar, and if some don't, then those who do will feel short-changed. You will also have some that will abuse the calendar. We all know it. Guilds that choose not to follow a claendar that they never approved of are simply protecting their interests against the people that they KNOW abuse it.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top">  Page  <b>1</b> <a href=http://pub96.ezboard.com/fkanebaylecommunitycenterfrm1.showMessageRange?topicID=196.topic&start=21&stop=39>2</a> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub96.ezboard.com/fkanebaylecommunitycenterfrm1.showPrevMessage?topicID=196.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub96.ezboard.com/fkanebaylecommunitycenterfrm1.showNextMessage?topicID=196.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a href=http://pub96.ezboard.com/fkanebaylecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=196.topic&index=20><img src=http://members.aol.com/jimturner99/addreply border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub96.ezboard.com/fkanebaylecommunity